11:28.655 --> 11:33.459 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This is part of what's going on.
It's part
of the dynamic of rising costs
in health care

11:33.493 --> 11:35.261 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
in the United States.

11:35.295 --> 11:37.864 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Is there any way of
knowing how
widespread this is? I know it
shows up in

11:37.897 --> 11:42.168 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
our premiums, but is it also
that if you put
together all these different
orphan drugs,

11:42.201 --> 11:45.271 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
you actually end up with quite a
population
of affected people?

11:45.305 --> 11:48.975 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SABRINA TAVERNISE: Well, some of
the kind
of gaming of the system that
drug companies

11:49.008 --> 11:54.247 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
have been doing under this act
is, they will
take a broader disease, say,
breast cancer,

11:54.280 --> 12:01.821 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
and slice it into narrow
definitions of smaller,
smaller kind of subsets of that
disease.

12:01.854 --> 12:06.926 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Then they can qualify for orphan
drug status,
when, in fact, the population is
much larger.

12:06.960 --> 12:11.064 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Another example has been a drug
that's been
approved for some other
treatment that they

12:11.097 --> 12:16.569 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
want to just sort of extend
their monopoly
on. And they under the act get
it approved

12:16.603 --> 12:21.774 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
for some -- for a new treatment,
but, effectively,
it's the same drug. There's no
new research

12:21.808 --> 12:25.445 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that has gone into it, no new
work, no new
invention. It's just sort of a
repackaging.

12:25.478 --> 12:28.081 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, these are some of the ways
that the law
has been abused.

12:28.114 --> 12:32.318 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Many, many ways to
get to the
same end, which is a profit.

12:32.352 --> 12:34.887 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Sabrina Tavernise, thank you
very much.

12:34.921 --> 12:42.061 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
SABRINA TAVERNISE: Thank you so
much.

12:42.095 --> 12:48.034 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: It is a journey of a
lifetime.

12:48.067 --> 12:54.540 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Journalist Paul Salopek spent
his career covering
the news overseas and jetting
around the globe,

12:54.574 --> 13:00.213 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
until he realized that walking
around the
world might provide deeper
insight.

13:00.246 --> 13:05.218 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Earlier this year, Hari
Sreenivasan traveled
to the Republic of Georgia to
take a stroll

13:05.251 --> 13:07.053 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
with Salopek.

13:07.086 --> 13:11.924 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It was such a memorable walk
that we decided
it was worth showing it to you
again tonight.

13:11.958 --> 13:16.396 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SALOPEK, Fellow, National
Geographic:
There is something not in your
brain, but

13:16.429 --> 13:21.901 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
almost in your backbone, about
the rhythm
of walking, this A/B, A/B. It's
the pace of

13:21.934 --> 13:23.836 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
a heartbeat.

13:23.870 --> 13:29.375 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: On a high
country cool morning,
Paul Salopek is out for a walk.
But his walk

13:29.409 --> 13:36.449 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is unlike any you or I might
take. On this
morning, he is nearing mile
4,000 of a trek

13:36.482 --> 13:42.922 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
