Ethiopia's Great
Rift Valley, the wellspring of
ancient humankind.

13:42.955 --> 13:47.560 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SALOPEK: This whole project
is about
two things. It's about the past
and the future.

13:47.593 --> 13:52.065 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And the past element is
following our first
ancestors who spread out of
Africa during

13:52.098 --> 13:57.770 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the Stone Age, so, following the
footsteps
of some very old and intrepid
pioneers.

13:57.804 --> 14:02.675 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: He calls this
project the
Out of Eden Walk, and he will
end it some

14:02.709 --> 14:10.750 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
time in six or seven years at
the very southern
tip of South America, after
logging 21,000

14:10.783 --> 14:16.756 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
miles. That's about 30 million
footsteps,
for those of you counting yours
every day.

14:16.789 --> 14:20.993 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
The two-time Pulitzer
Prize-winning foreign
correspondent was used to
dropping into war

14:21.027 --> 14:27.533 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
zones and driving his way out as
fast as possible.
But so far on this trip, he's
walked through

14:27.567 --> 14:34.440 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
